{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658057"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:41:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:41:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20704"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20704"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13580"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95613"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13580"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20704"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78424"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"5242"},{"type":"tags","id":"11578"},{"type":"tags","id":"11742"},{"type":"tags","id":"12444"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32641"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32642"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95613"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EProteasomes are essential cellular structures involved in protein quality control and regulation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of proteasomes in cellular protein degradation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Unfold proteins for chaperone-mediated refolding","Degrade polyubiquitinated proteins into peptide fragments","Digest proteins within lysosomes","Transport proteins to the extracellular space","Synthesise ubiquitin for protein tagging"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that proteasomes \u003Cstrong\u003Edegrade polyubiquitinated proteins into peptide fragments\u003C/strong\u003E. Proteasomes are cylindrical protein complexes that contain multiple protease activities with active sites pointed toward the hollow core. They recognise proteins that have been tagged with ubiquitin chains (polyubiquitinated), unfold these proteins, and digest them into small peptide fragments of approximately 6-12 amino acids in length. These fragments can then be further degraded to individual amino acids for recycling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUnfold proteins for chaperone-mediated refolding\u003C/strong\u003E - While proteasomes do unfold proteins, they do so as part of the degradation process, not to facilitate refolding. Molecular chaperones, not proteasomes, assist in protein refolding.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDigest proteins within lysosomes\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the function of lysosomal enzymes, not proteasomes. Lysosomes are membrane-bound organelles that degrade material taken up by endocytosis or autophagy, whereas proteasomes are cytosolic protein complexes.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport proteins to the extracellular space\u003C/strong\u003E - Proteasomes do not transport proteins out of the cell; they degrade them within the cytosol.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesise ubiquitin for protein tagging\u003C/strong\u003E - Proteasomes do not synthesise ubiquitin. Ubiquitin is synthesised separately and attached to target proteins by a series of enzymes (E1, E2, and E3 ligases).\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProteasomes play a crucial role in cellular housekeeping by eliminating denatured or misfolded proteins that could otherwise form toxic aggregates. They also regulate the concentration of various proteins involved in cell signalling, cell cycle progression, and other critical cellular processes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Proteasomes are cellular structures that degrade cytosolic proteins including denatured, misfolded, or regulated proteins.","Ubiquitin is a small protein that tags molecules for degradation through covalent binding.","Proteasomes break down proteins into small peptide fragments (6-12 amino acids) that can be further degraded to amino acids for recycling."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 1, The Cell as a Unit of Health and Disease;  p. 15"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78424"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20704"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78424","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78424"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-28T19:09:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-28T19:19:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13580"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95613"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5242"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Proteasomes","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-23T16:04:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-23T16:04:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"